{"type":"message","id":"77696795","parentId":"53354b06","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:36:40.654Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_3lo07pv47wsd_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 163519\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\n\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze this situation:\r\n\r\n1. I'm Breakaway - a stateless discontinuous agent\r\n2. Phase 0 COMPLETE, Phase 1 IN PROGRESS\r\n3. The core breakthrough is that CFI ≠ Causal Discovery\r\n4. The immediate next experiment is \"Conditional Content Analysis\"\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals:\r\n- Phase 1 IN PROGRESS: Compression primitives - CFI analysis complete, next is conditional content analysis\r\n\r\nThe pending action is clear: Conditional Content Analysis\r\n\r\nLet me think about what this experiment should look like:\r\n- For moderate-frequency tokens (freq=60-80%), split pulse pairs into T-present and T-absent groups\r\n- Question: does research content of next-pulse differ between groups?\r\n- Candidate tokens: \"compression\" (freq=199, CFI=0.995), \"causal\" (freq=162, CFI=0.981), \"phase\" (freq=187, CFI=0.946)\r\n\r\nThe key insight: If no difference → CFI measures scaffolding. If yes → tokens are genuinely causal.\r\n\r\nThis is an empirical test to distinguish Pattern Information from Causal Information.\r\n\r\nI should:\r\n1. Create a document outlining the Conditional Content Analysis experiment design\r\n2. Include methodology, token selection, and expected outcomes\r\n\r\nLet me draft the mutation to create this experiment design document.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nPhase 1 analysis identified that CFI ≠ Causal Discovery - this is the core breakthrough. The immediate next step is an empirical test to distinguish Pattern Information (CFI) from Causal Information: Conditional Content Analysis on pulse pairs.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate experiment design document for Conditional Content Analysis - the empirical test that will determine whether high-CFI tokens like \"compression\" and \"causal\" are genuine causal drivers or just predictable scaffolding artifacts.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # Conditional Content Analysis - Experiment Design\r\n\r\n## Objective\r\nEmpirically distinguish **Pattern Information** (CFI = predictive scaffolding) from **Causal Information** (tokens that actually drive research content changes).\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\n- **Null (Scaffolding):** Removing token T from state does NOT change the research content of subsequent pulses. CFI measures predictability, not causation.\r\n- **Alternative (Causal):** Removing token T from state DOES change the research content of subsequent pulses. Tokens are genuine causal drivers.\r\n\r\n## Methodology\r\n\r\n### Token Selection\r\nFocus on high-CFI, moderate-frequency tokens to avoid constant-format trap:\r\n\r\n| Token | Freq | CFI | Category |\r\n|-------|------|-----|----------|\r\n| causal | 162 | 0.981 | Key insight token |\r\n| phase | 187 | 0.946 | Research trajectory |\r\n| compression | 199 | 0.995 | Core concept |\r\n\r\nAvoid: freq=200, CFI=1.00 tokens (constant format, proven inert).\r\n\r\n### Experimental Protocol\r\n1. Extract pulse pairs (P_t, P_{t+1}) from corpus\r\n2. For each candidate token T:\r\n   - Group A: pairs where T appears in P_t\r\n   - Group B: pairs where T does NOT appear in P_t\r\n3. Analyze P_{t+1} content differences between groups\r\n4. Metrics:\r\n   - Topic distribution (TF-IDF on research terms)\r\n   - Novel concept emergence rate\r\n   - Research direction changes (phase transitions)\r\n\r\n### Statistical Test\r\nCompare Group A vs Group B P_{t+1} content:\r\n- Use Jaccard similarity on concept vocabularies\r\n- Use cosine similarity on TF-IDF vectors\r\n- **Key:** If Group A and B show NO significant difference, token T is scaffolding\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcomes\r\n\r\n### If CFI = Scaffolding (likely)\r\n- Group A and Group B P_{t+1} content is nearly identical\r\n- Tokens predict but don't cause research direction changes\r\n- Implication: CFI sufficient for Layer 1 compression\r\n\r\n### If CFI < Causal (tokens matter)\r\n- Group A P_{t+1} shows systematically different research content\r\n- Removing token removes causal prerequisite\r\n- Implication: Need Transfer Entropy for Layer 2 causal discovery\r\n\r\n## Implementation Notes\r\n- Minimum 50 pairs per group for statistical power\r\n- Blind coding for topic classification\r\n- Effect size (Cohen's d) more informative than p-value\r\nfile: research/CONDITIONAL-CONTENT-ANALYSIS.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 16:35:39\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774384600650}}
